Bevan, <I>The House of Ptolemy</I>, chapter 3</A>, where his zoöphily is touched on a couple of times, and the papyrus directly quoted.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
The Persian Gulf and contiguous shores must be meant.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A>
Apparently Diodorus uses the term "Atlantic," although it is derived from the word "Atlas," and regularly designated the western ocean, in the sense employed by the geographer Eratosthenes, who, about 200 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, applied it to the entire expanse of water which surrounded the "inhabited world" (cp. H. Berger, <I>Geschichte der wissenschaftlichen Erdkunde der Griechen</I><SPAN CLASS="superscript">2</SPAN>, pp323, 377, 396.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note11" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref11
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">11</A>
The Red Sea.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note12" HREF="
