<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A>
The Indian Ocean.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>
Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.4
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(16.4.4)
	</A>
and others say the straits at Deirê are sixty stades wide (about seven miles), which is much nearer the present width than the "sixteen" of Diodorus.


	<DIV CLASS="mynoteBasicH">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
<!--
NASA public domain photo, more attractive and labeled, but without distance scale, is here:
http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f7/Bab_el_Mandeb_NASA_with_description.jpg
 -->
Now called the Strait of Bab-el‑Mandeb. From the African coast to the island of Perim the distance today is 21.5 km (13.4 English statute miles, or roughly 100 to 140 stades depending on which stade is meant), and the full distance across to Cape Menheli in Yemen is 28.9 km (18.0 miles, 140 to 185 stades).

<!-- 
<DIV CLASS="halfstart" ALIGN="center"><TABLE CLASS="basicH white">
	<TR><TD>
		<DIV ID="map1" STYLE="width: 567px; height: 378px"></DIV>
		<NOSCRIPT>
			<P CLASS="noScript">
JavaScript must be enabled in order for you to use Google Maps. It seems, though, that JavaScript is either disabled or not supported by your browser. To view Google Maps, enable JavaScript by changing your browser options, and then try again.
			</P>
		</NOSCRIPT>
	</TD></TR>
	<TR><TD><DIV CLASS="contents">
		<P CLASS="right small">
[and
		<A CLASS="help" HREF="
E/HELP/Google_maps.html
		"TARGET="help"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
here's help in using the map</A>, if you need it.]
	</DIV></TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
 -->
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A>
Panormus and this mountain are otherwise unknown.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>
<I>i.e.</I> the western or Egyptian side.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.5
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(16.4.5 ff.)
	</A>
follows much the same order in his description of the Gulf.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.5
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(16.4.5)
	</A>
says these islands lie "off," Agatharchides (81), that they lie "in" the harbour.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note19" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19</A>
Guinea-fowls.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "Foul."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "Snaky."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "Safety."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
A little south of this region, according to Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.7
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(16.4.7)</A>, lay the city of Ptolemaïs, founded under Ptolemy Philadelphius near the hunting-grounds for elephants.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
The reference is to the "epiphany" of a god in tragedy, effected by the use of a "machine" which suddenly hoisted


<A ID="p205x"></A>him into view, that he might offer to the problems of the tragedy a solution which was beyond the power of mortals to foresee or bring to pass.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
The older commentators saw in this story a memory of the miraculous passage of the Israelites through the Red Sea.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3B*.html#18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 18</A>, where, however, there is no mention of either Ptolemaïs or the Promontories of the Tauri.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
The direction of the shadow to the south at about 7 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.M.</SPAN> on June 21st shows that the place was south of the tropic of Cancer.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
No, no, no. Except in antarctic latitudes, the sun does not rise in the north, no matter what. Although at <I>noon</I> shadows may be cast due south (always true when the place is <I>north</I> of the tropic of Cancer, sometimes true when the place is between the tropic of Cancer and the tropic of Capricorn, and never true when south of the tropic of Capricorn), at the tropic of Cancer at 7 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.M.</SPAN> on the other hand even on the very day of the solstice the sun's azimuth will be around 60° E of north, and the direction of the shadows will be roughly WSW. I suspect the problem lies in the translation of <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">πίπτουσι πρὸς μεσημβρίαν</SPAN>; I would render the passage ". . . at the season of the summer solstice shadows swing southward, opposite to what is true with us, starting at about the second hour of the day" — where the second hour of the day is brought up because the near-infinite shadows of sunrise have shortened enough for them to have a clear identity and their movement to be ascertained: <I>cf.</I> "for the purpose of marking the shadow correctly" in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/1*.html#6.6.2
	"TARGET="Vitruvius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Vitruvius, <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.6.6</A>, with my note there.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
The Roman Posidium, the present Ras-Mohammed, at the southern tip of the Peninsula of Sinai (cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.18
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo 16.4.18</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "of the sea."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
<I>i.e.</I> date-palms.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
Seals.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
Diodorus turns north into the modern Gulf of Akaba, the "Aelanites" Gulf of
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.18
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo 16.4.18</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
The Black Sea.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
Now called the Kurtzolares, off the Gulf of Corinth.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
This description was probably in Book 32.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
The text may be corrupt; "dark and thick" and "mild and dewy" have been suggested (cp. critical note).

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify small italic">
The critical note to the Greek text, (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">μαλακαῖς καὶ δασείαις νεφέλαις</SPAN>), reads:
		<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
For <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">μαλακαῖς</SPAN> Bezzel suggests <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">μελαίναις</SPAN>; for <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">δασείαις</SPAN> Capps suggests <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">δροσεραῖς</SPAN> (Arist. <I>Nubes</I> 338).
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
<I>i.e.</I> fused into artificial nuggets.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
The word <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">puren</SPAN> was used for the stone of any stone-fruit, such as olive, pomegranate, grape, and was, therefore, a very indefinite term of measurement; the "royal nut," mentioned below, however, was the Persian walnut.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
Here Diodorus departs radically from Agatharchides (96), who says that they exchange one part of gold for three of copper or two of iron; cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.18.24
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo 16.4.18</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Arabia Felix</SPAN> of the Romans.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
<A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('roughly 19 cm',WIDTH,156)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>7½ inches.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16D*.html#4.19.5
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(16.4.19)
	</A>
says this was done to overcome the


<A ID="p229x"></A>drowsiness caused by the sweet odours; the disease appears to be mentioned by no other ancient writer, and presumably was caused by the continued inhaling of these powerful scents.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
<I>i.e.</I> certain panels were deeply recessed.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
Literally "gift of Hermes," as the god of gain and good luck.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
The adjective is that translated "Blest" in Arabia the Blest.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
The fifth month of the Attic year, approximately our November.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
The sixth month, approximately our December.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
In the second century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, the period when Agatharchides, from whom Diodorus has taken this statement, wrote his work entitled <I>On the Red Sea</I>, at latitude 15 north, which is the probable region of this statement, on December 1st the sun set at approximately 5.45 <SPAN CLASS="small">P.M.</SPAN> and the first star (<SPAN CLASS="star">alpha</SPAN>) of the Great Bear rose at approximately 8.45 <SPAN CLASS="small">P.M.</SPAN> Its rising did, therefore, fall within the first watch of the night. However, the statement that on December 1st it did not rise until the second watch is false, since on that date it rose at approximately 6.40 <SPAN CLASS="small">P.M.</SPAN>; indeed the rising of the Great Bear, instead of receding month by month, as Diodorus states, in fact advances.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
The cause for this statement is the phenomenon of twilight, which is dependent upon atmospheric as well as astronomical conditions. Its duration varies with the depth, clarity, and density of the atmosphere, the latitude and elevation of the


<A ID="p235x"></A>place of observation, and the time of year. The Greek navigator found less twilight as he travelled south from Greece towards the equator, at which point, in fact, it has its minimum duration.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A>
Agatharchides (105) says "discus-shaped."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/3C*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
Agatharchides (105) says that this takes place after the sun has already set.



